text: Back Safety in the Workplace 1 Back Safety in the Workplace Introduction The Occupational Safety and Health Administration also known as OSHA, does not have a specific regulation for back safety, but training employees to lift safely is implied by the General Duty Clause of the Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970. The law requires employers to provide employees with a workplace that is “free of recognized hazards.” OSHA has stated that it will not focus its enforcement efforts on

employers that have implemented effective ergonomic programs or that are making effort to reduce hazards that cause worker strains and sprains. “Ergonomics” is the science of designing the workplace, keeping in mind the capabilities and limitations of the worker. Poor worksite design leads to fatigued, frustrated and injured workers. A safe and ergonomically friendly environment can reduce injuries and increase productivity and employee satisfaction. Back Injury Statistics Back injuries can be

extremely painful and long-lasting. The Federal Bureau of Labor Statistics estimates more than 1 million workers incur back injuries each year with lower back problems accounting for 80% of the claims reported. According to OSHA, back injuries are the nation’s number one workplace safety problem and account for nearly 20% of all injuries and illnesses in the workplace.There are more than 264 million lost workdays each year; that’s two workdays for every full- time employee in the United States.

These injuries cost employers and insurance providers in the United States more than $50 billion annually. Back injuries are the top cause of job-related disability claims. Up to one-third of back injuries could be prevented through a better designed workspace and proper use of personal protective equipment. Common Causes of Injuries Lifting a heavy object. When job requires heavy lifting, make sure to use equipment when possible or ask for help. Try to avoid repetitive lifting over a long

period of time or twisting the spine while lifting. Twisting. Avoid twisting at the waist while lifting or holding a heavy load. Back Safety in the Workplace 2 Reaching & Lifting. An injury usually occurs when reaching over the head, across a table or out the back of a vehicle, try to find alternative ways to reduce reaching, such as optimizing staging areas. Carrying & Lifting. Get help or use equipment when carrying or lifting objects with awkward or odd shapes as this may cause lower back

problems. Awkward Positions. Poor posture can contribute to back pain which may be caused by poor workstation layout and/or equipment design. Make sure that workstations, monitors, and chairs are properly adjusted. Slips, Trips & Falls. It is very easy to injure your back, neck or legs while slipping, tripping, or falling. Walk the intended path to ensure there are no hazards as carrying large objects may obscure your view. Also, if you see a trip hazard or liquid on the floor, be sure to clean

it up or properly identify the hazard to prevent others from injury. Sitting or Standing. Too long in one position can be very hard on the lower back. It is recommended to alternate at least once every hour for at least five minutes. Lifting Safety Procedures Proper lifting procedures and load-carrying techniques are crucial for preventing painful and expensive injuries in the workplace. Unfortunately, most workers do not consistently use back safety practices. Back injuries are often caused by

unsafe lifting and carrying of heavy or awkward objects but are easily preventable. Always warm-up your back and legs before performing any lifting task. It is important to prepare your body for work by using the following exercises and techniques: Low Back Rotation Stretch. Stand with hands on hips. Stabilizing the hips and legs, gently roll your upper body forward, right, backward, and left to stretch your lower back. Perform 8 slow circles gradually expanding the circle each time. Hamstring &

Achilles Stretch in opposite directions. Position your body with one leg forward and the toes of that foot raised up. Keep your back straight while you bend forward at the waist. You should feel a stretch in the back of your thigh and knee. Then shift your weight onto your forward leg and bend knee, keep the back leg straight and heel on floor. Hold each stretch for 20 seconds. Perform each stretch 4 times for each leg. Before Lifting Any Object Plan ahead: Know what you are lifting and how you

will lift it. Be aware of the weight of the object. Determine whether it is safe to lift on your own or if you will need assistance. Make sure the work area is flat, dry, and clear of debris. Back Safety in the Workplace 3 Check your pathway: Make sure the lift pathway is clear. Remove any tripping hazards or debris. Check for any wet or slick surfaces. Use ergonomic equipment: Use lift assists, forklift, dolly, cart, hand truck or hoist. Make sure you are trained before using the equipment. Get

help when needed: When lifting awkward or heavy loads, utilize a two-person lift. Make sure you lift at the same time and keep the load level. Lastly, wear proper Personal Protective Equipment also known as PPE: This would include protective eyewear, shoes, and gloves as appropriate for the situation. Basic Diagonal Lifting Technique • Get as close to the object as possible; • Use a wide stance with one foot forward and to the side of the object for good balance; • Keep your back straight, push

your buttocks out, and use your legs and hips to lower yourself down to the object; • Slide the object as close to you as possible; • Put your hand that is on the same side of your body as the forward foot on the side of the object furthest from you; • Put your other hand on the side of the object closest to you. Your hands should be on opposite corners; • Grasp the object firmly with both hands; • Prepare for the lift, tighten your core muscles, look forward and upward, keep a straight and

strong back; • Lift slowly and follow your head and shoulders. Hold the load close to your body; Lift by extending your legs with your back straight and breathe out as you lift. • While walking or stepping be sure to know your surroundings, you may also choose to have a spotter identify any potential hazards or steps. Ergonomic Workstation Many of us spend hours at our workstations every day. Bad habits and incorrect posture can lead to neck and back pain or sore wrists and fingers. Proper

ergonomics can help you stay comfortable at work. Ergonomics is a scientific discipline, which is concerned with improving the productivity, health, safety, and comfort of people. It is important that you adjust your workstation furniture and equipment to suit your individual needs. A good chair provides the necessary support to the back, legs, buttocks, and arms, while reducing exposures to awkward postures and forceful exertions. • Push your hips as far back as they can go in the chair; •

Adjust the seat height so your feet are flat on the floor and your knees are equal to or slightly lower than your hips. Use a footrest if necessary; Back Safety in the Workplace 4 • Adjust the back of the chair. Make sure your upper and lower back are supported. Use inflatable cushions or small pillows if necessary. If you have an active back mechanism on your chair, use it to make frequent position changes; • Adjust the armrests so that your shoulders are relaxed. If your armrests are in the

way, remove them. Monitor Choosing a suitable monitor and placing it in an appropriate position helps reduce exposure to forceful exertions, awkward postures, and overhead glare. This helps prevent possible health effects such as excessive fatigue, eyestrain, and neck and back pain. • Center the monitor above your keyboard, directly in front of you; • Position the top of the monitor approximately 2 to 3 inches above seated eye level. If you wear bifocals, lower the monitor to a comfortable

reading level; • Sit at least an arm’s length away from the screen, and then adjust the distance for your vision. Keyboard and Mouse Proper selection and arrangement of the computer keyboard and mouse help reduce exposure to awkward postures, repetition, and contact stress. • Put the keyboard directly in front of you; • Keep shoulders relaxed and your elbows close to your body; • Maintain your wrists straight and in-line with your forearms; • Keep the mouse close to the keyboard; • Alternate

hands with which you operate the mouse; • Use keyboard shortcuts to reduce extended use. Recommendations for Maintaining a Healthy Back Sustain a healthy weight. Individuals who are overweight are at greater risk for back pain, joint pain, and muscle strain than those who are not overweight. This is especially true for individuals with extra weight in their stomach area because this excess weight pulls the pelvis forward and strains the lower back. A healthy, well balanced diet accompanied by a

safe exercise program will help you achieve or maintain a healthy weight. Get quality rest. It is very important to get enough sleep during the night and to sleep in a position that maintains a natural alignment of the spine. However, it is also important to maintain an active lifestyle if you want to reduce your risk of developing back pain. The most common of lower back problems are muscular in origin, and if the muscles are not moved and stretched regularly, they become tight, short, and

stiff, eventually resulting in back pain and injury. Back Safety in the Workplace 5 Maintain good posture. Correct posture and body mechanics result in less pressure on the discs and less strain to the muscles, ligaments, and back joints. When your posture is right and you move your body correctly, you reduce your risk of back injury. Reduce stress. Stress increases tension in all your muscles, including your back muscles. Therefore, stress-reduction techniques like deep breathing and meditation

may help you reduce your risk of back pain and injury. Stay flexible, do exercises. Inflexibility in the form of tight hamstrings and a limited range of motion in the mid-body section can increase your risk of back injury or make existing back pain worse. Some forms of exercise, such as yoga, Pilates, and tai-chi, may help relieve or prevent back pain by increasing flexibility.
